Also sorry that there isn't that much information in this bug report. I didn't test which version exactly broke this. I have moved all development to Clang to avoid this issue.




* **Version**: 19.12 (does not happen on earlier versions AFAIK)
* **Where did you get dlib**: Hunter
* **Platform**: Linux x86-64
* **Compiler**: GCC 6.3 and GCC 8.1 tested (failing). Clang 4-6 and MSVC 2017 working as expected.

cppclean seems to be clever enough to determine that you can have a `std::shared_ptr<X>` to a forward-declared type `X`, which is good.

Unfortunately, if the name is hidden behind an [alias declaration](http://en.cppreference.com/w/cpp/language/type_alias), cppclean then warns that `X` must be #included.  The following test code demonstrates the issue:

```
#include <memory>

// Forward declaration of class X is all that is required to have a std::shared_ptr
class X;

// Alias declaration - requires C++11
template<typename T>
using MySharedPtr = std::shared_ptr<T>;

struct A
{
  MySharedPtr<X> x;
};
```

For this case, cppclean prints:
```
cppclean_test5.h:4: 'X' forward declared, but needs to be #included
```

On the other hand, if you change the line `MySharedPtr<X> x;` to simply `std::shared_ptr<X> x;`, the warning goes away.  So I guess this is  really more of a feature request to better handle alias declarations, as we use this technique to handle backwards compatibility with older compilers in our library.

Jedi 0.10.3

Using goto_assignments with follow_imports=True on `foo` in code like the following seems to navigate to `@decorator`

```
@decorator()
def foo():
    pass

foo()
```

I debugged it, and in this case in `filter_follow_imports` in `jedi/api/__init__.py` the name is an instance of TreeNameDefinition and calling name.infer() gives the wrapper function.

I changed the code to look like this, and it seems to improve things, but I haven't looked at the Jedi code enough to know if this is the right approach

```
        def filter_follow_imports(names):
            for name in names:
                if isinstance(name, imports.ImportName):
                    for context in name.infer():
                        yield context.name
                elif isinstance(name, TreeNameDefinition) and name.tree_name.get_definition().type in ('import_name', 'import_from'):
                    for context in name.infer():
                        yield context.name
                else:
                    yield name
```

