	prefix m;

	container con {
		list lis {
			key "item-id";
			ordered-by system;
			leaf item-id { type uint32; }
			leaf item-data { type uint32; }
		}
	}
}
```

I generated the python modules by running:
```
export PYBINDPLUGIN=`/usr/bin/env python -c 'import pyangbind; import os; print "%s/plugin" % os.path.dirname(pyangbind.__file__)'`
pyang --plugindir $PYBINDPLUGIN -f pybind --use-xpathhelper --split-class-dir model model.yang
```

Then, when you run the next python code:
```
import json
from model.con import con
from pyangbind.lib import pybindJSON
from pyangbind.lib.serialise import pybindIETFJSONEncoder, pybindJSONEncoder 

def normalizeJSON(data):
    return(json.dumps(json.loads(data), separators=(',', ': ')))

c = con()
e1 = c.lis.add(1)
e1.item_data = 111
e2 = c.lis.add(2)
e2.item_data = 222

ietf_encoder = pybindIETFJSONEncoder()
default_encoder = pybindJSONEncoder()

print 'dumps(mode=ietf)..............:', normalizeJSON(pybindJSON.dumps(c, mode='ietf'))
print 'dumps(mode=default)...........:', normalizeJSON(pybindJSON.dumps(c, mode='default'))
print 'pybindIETFJSONEncoder:encode():', normalizeJSON(ietf_encoder.encode(c))
print 'pybindJSONEncoder:encode()....:', normalizeJSON(default_encoder.encode(c))
```

The output I get is:
```
dumps(mode=ietf)..............: {"model:lis": [{"item-data": 111,"item-id": 1},{"item-data": 222,"item-id": 2}]}
dumps(mode=default)...........: {"lis": {"1": {"item-data": 111,"item-id": 1},"2": {"item-data": 222,"item-id": 2}}}
pybindIETFJSONEncoder:encode(): {"lis": {"1": {"item-data": 111,"item-id": 1},"2": {"item-data": 222,"item-id": 2}}}
pybindJSONEncoder:encode()....: {"lis": {"1": {"item-data": 111,"item-id": 1},"2": {"item-data": 222,"item-id": 2}}}
```

In my understanding result for pybindIETFJSONEncoder:encode should be exactly the same than dumps(mode=ietf), right?
NOTE: normalizeJSON method is just to normalize indentations and new lines in resulting JSON data.

Cheers,
Lluis

